  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem requires deriving the force law for a polymer under adiabatic conditions. This necessitates first finding the partition function and entropy of the freely jointed chain, and then applying the adiabatic constraint (constant entropy) to find the force-extension relationship.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "thermodynamics_derivation",
      "instructions": "Derive the canonical partition function Z for a freely jointed polymer chain of n segments of length l extended to a total end-to-end distance x. From this partition function, derive the Helmholtz free energy A(x, T) and the entropy S(x, T) as functions of x and T. Ensure the dependence on n, l, k, and T is explicitly clear."
    },
    {
      "label": "adiabatic_constraint_solver",
      "instructions": "Given the entropy function S(x, T) derived by the previous agent, formulate the mathematical constraint for an adiabatic process where dS = 0. Use this constraint to express the temperature T as a function of the extension x. Then, use the thermodynamic relation for force F = -(dF/dx)_S or F = T(dS/dx)_T to derive the final force law F(x) under the condition of constant entropy."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent agent will take the entropy function S(x, T) from helper 1 and the adiabatic constraint dS=0 from helper 2 to solve for T(x). Finally, the parent will substitute T(x) into the thermodynamic force equation to obtain the exact F(x) formula."
}

